Jun 24 2009 	Good Hotel Scary Location	We stayed at this hotel for two nights in June 2009. We chose this hotel because we had a rental car. If you are just planning to explore San Francisco, I would not recommend renting a vehicle, but we needed the car to get to a few destinations outside of town. Our room rate was $93/night and parking at this hotel was an additional $20/night. Many of the hotels near Union Square charge $45-50 plus tax per night for parking alone, so that's why we ended up at the Carriage Inn. We were always able to get a spot in the underground parkade, but the lot is not very big and one night we almost got the last spot.If you are saddled with a car, then you might want to consider the Best Western Carriage Inn. The hotel rooms are clean and comfortable. The rooms were redone in the summer of 2008. Our room was quiet (unlike many hotels in San Francisco which have paper thin walls) and I slept well. A mini fridge would have been a nice touch, as there is really nowhere to walk for a drink or snack. Coffee is provided, although if you are a coffee conoisseur, be warned that it is Nescafe instant! There is free wireless Internet access in the rooms, although it takes about 10 minutes to get through the secure login process on your device.The biggest downside is the hotel's location. The hotel is located about three long blocks (or a 10-15 minute walk) from Westfield, a great shopping centre. We chose the hotel in part because it was still fairly close to the shopping district around Westfield and Union Square.However, the reason the hotel's parking is cheaper than the hotels along Union Square is that the hotel is located &quot;south of Market&quot; (i.e. SOMA). SOMA is generally described as an up and coming neighbourhood undergoing revitalisation, but it definitely has a long way to go. I have been to San Francisco before and knew what I was getting, but if you don't know what SOMA is like, you should know before you go. For the Canadians out there, SOMA is about ten times worse than Vancouver's legendary east side and I am not exaggerating. If you set foot outside the hotel at any hour, you can expect to see dozens of derelicts - people on every corner having conversations with themselves and waving their hands frantically, people passed out alongside buildings, and beggars everywhere (some aggressive, some not). The neighbourhood is slightly better on weekdays than during the day on weekends. I would not recommed setting foot outside after dark.If you are saddled with a car and want a hotel that is centrally located, you might want to consider the Carriage Inn. After all, the rooms are clean and comfortable. Personally, I will not stay in SOMA again until I have seen more evidence of the neighbourhood's revitalisation.If you want to be able to walk to shopping and restaurants and comfortably walk in and our of your hotel, then do not choose any hotel in SOMA.	
