Jan 21 2008 	Great Value Great Little Hotel Perfect Central Location	I was in San Francisco for the MacWorld Conference. I was looking for a reasonably priced, centrally located hotel within walking distance of some of the things I wanted to see in San Francisco during my visit. The hotel was booked based on price and TripAdvisor reviews.Let me hit the highlights1) You can take BART from the San Fran airport and get off at Civic Center, only 3-4 blocks from the hotel. I would recommend a morning flight, as the streets in downtown San Fran in this neighborhood can be a little scary on certain blocks. If I arrived at night, I personally would shell out the $45 for a taxi. Like any urban environment, you have to just be vigilant. It is really only the two blocks closest to the hotel that had some questionable personalities, once you get closer into downtown, the crowds increase and things are comfortable.2) The hotel staff were very friendly. We were allowed to check in early and they were always prompt to help us if we had a special request.3) The outside of the hotel isn't extraordinary, but the inside is clean and neatly appointed (see photo of room).4) One of my favorite things was a free daily continental breakfast delivered to the room. Simply fill out a card before 11 PM and hang it on your door. I had coffee, orange juice, muffin, cereal and fruit every morning. It was perfect. There is also a fridge and coffee maker in the room.5) One of the great things about the location is that my friend and I could walk to great sites or catch a cable car all within a few blocks of the hotel. We could catch a bus ($1.50) down to the Wharf and out to Alcatraz, or a Cable Car over to Coit Tower or China Town, etc.All in all, I would stay there again. There is another Best Western right across the street that is undergoing some great renovations, so check that one out as well if you like.	
Nov 18 2007 	A very good choice	San Francisco is quite run-down in many parts but the best way to see it is to use the public transport and get out into the various districts still within a mile of the centre. AND WALK. As Senior Citizens we paid 25p (50c) including a transfer ticket.The Carriage Inn, in 7th St, was very good. The staff were excellent. The free breakfast, brought to your room, was a marvellous service and was always served on time. The room on the second floor was quite adequate and had all that you would need. We switched off the frig as its humming was obtrusive.The hotel had a selection of tour brochures and booked us without fee for tours to Yosemite and the wineries in the Napa Valley. A tour company shuttle service then collects you and takes you to the departure point at Fishermans Wharf - and returns you to the hotel at the end of the day. We paid a deposit of $30 at the hotel and then used a credit card to pay the balance at Fishermans Wharf - all well organised. the guides and coaches were very good.The location of the Carriage Inn was very good, only 3 or 4 minutes walk from the trams and buses in Market Street. Despite what others have said about the vagrants, we, from the UK, felt quite safe - perhaps US citizens are that much less world-travelled and feel uncomfortable with anything out of their normal experience.The Cheesecake Factory restaurant is on the 8th floor of Macy's in Union Square; get a table on the balcony overlooking Union Square. For those who have not been to a Cheesecake Factory restaurant - it is just a name; it serves all types of food but in HUGE American glutton-size portions, quite insulting to those of us who eat in a responsible way. However, the quality iand service is very good.Saw only one McDonalds - that must be a record! The Westfield Shopping Centre (yes, Centre, it is Australian) in Market Street (8 minutes) is new and enormous and well worth a look even if you are not buying anything. It is a bit anonymous, hiding under the Bloomingdale's shop front.The pre-paid airport shuttle by Lorrie's was well worth buying in advance on the Internet and took us/collected us from the Carriage Inn.	
