Sep 20 2007 	"A" for Effort	The business hotels I usually stay in when I go to SF were unavailable for some reason (someone told me there was a big convention in town), so my assistant booked my 3 nights here. I was quite bummed at first -- older property in an unattractive, iffy part of town (I'm a businesswoman who travels alone, so a feeling of safety in the neighborhood is important to me), slightly stale cigarette-y smell. HOWEVER, after three nights there, I have to say that the main drawbacks to the hotel have to do with the dated physical property itself and the somewhat deserted neighborhood. Everything else was actually admirable: very clean, large, quiet rooms; friendly service; free wireless; nice size work desk; strong hot showers; an almost sweet attempt to keep the decor somewhat updated; relatively inexpensive price for an &quot;executive king&quot; with a seating area. The cigarette smell went away after the first day; maybe it was someone in the room next to me. The Vietnamese-Chinese restaurant next door that looks like a dive actually has very tasty, inexpensive food, and the hip burger place across the street has great breakfasts and really good coffee. Even though the bedding was far from luxury, somehow I slept like a rock for all three nights I was there. Not sure if I'd proactively choose to stay there again because I'm a little spoiled (I travel 1-4 times per month for business around the country), but if I HAD to, it would be just fine. I got a lot of work done there when I wasn't at client meetings.	
